{:pack/id "clojure"
 :pack/name "Clojure Conventions Pack"
 :pack/version "2026.01.22"
 :pack/description "Clojure and Polylith coding conventions"
 :pack/author "miniforge-official"
 :pack/license "Apache-2.0"

 :pack/extends
 [{:pack-id "foundations" :version-constraint ">=2026.01.01"}]

 :pack/categories
 [{:category/id "210"
   :category/name "Polylith Architecture"
   :category/rules [:210-interface-only-deps]}
  {:category/id "211"
   :category/name "Per-File Stratification"
   :category/rules [:211-layer-headings
                    :211-max-three-layers
                    :211-comment-block-last]}]

 :pack/rules
 [;;============================================================================
  ;; Category 210: Polylith Architecture
  ;;============================================================================

  {:rule/id :210-interface-only-deps
   :rule/title "Cross-component deps must target interface"
   :rule/description "Components may only depend on other components via their .interface namespace"
   :rule/severity :major
   :rule/category "210"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["components/**/src/**/*.clj" "components/**/src/**/*.cljc"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :content-scan
    :patterns [;; Importing .core directly from another component
               "\\[ai\\.miniforge\\.\\w+\\.core\\s"
               "\\[ai\\.miniforge\\.\\w+\\.impl\\s"
               ;; require with .core or .impl suffix
               "require.*\\.core\\]"
               "require.*\\.impl\\]"]}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "For cross-component calls, target ...<other>.interface - surface a fix if .core is used.

    Polylith architecture rules:
    - Workspace: components/, bases/, projects/
    - Cross-component deps must target ...<component>.interface (not .core)
    - bases can depend on component interfaces
    - projects can depend on bases and component interfaces
    - components may depend on other components only via their .interface ns
    - Never depend on projects from bases or components

    WRONG: [ai.miniforge.agent.core :as agent-core]
    RIGHT: [ai.miniforge.agent.interface :as agent]

    When you see a violation, suggest changing the require to use .interface instead."

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :hard-halt
    :message "Direct dependency on component implementation: %s"
    :remediation "Change to .interface namespace"}}

  ;;============================================================================
  ;; Category 211: Per-File Stratification
  ;;============================================================================

  {:rule/id :211-layer-headings
   :rule/title "Use layer headings in namespaces"
   :rule/description "Structure each ns with labeled strata as headings"
   :rule/severity :minor
   :rule/category "211"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["components/**/src/**/*.clj" "bases/**/src/**/*.clj"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :content-scan
    ;; Multiple defns without any layer separator comment between them
    :patterns ["\\)\\s*\\n\\s*\\(defn\\s"]}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "When creating/editing a namespace:
    1) Insert/maintain Layer 0/1/2 headings: ;-------------- Layer N
    2) Keep them monotonic increasing (0 -> 1 -> 2)
    3) Keep pure helpers in Layer 0
    4) Put orchestration in higher layers

    Example structure:
    ;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 0
    ;; Pure helpers and value-level functions

    (defn helper-fn [x] ...)

    ;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 1
    ;; Functions that compose Layer 0

    (defn orchestrate-fn [data] ...)

    ;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 2
    ;; Entry points and side-effecting operations

    (defn main-entry [args] ...)

    Reverse DAG: Layer 0 at top (pure/value-level); higher layers may call lower ones but not vice-versa."

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :warn
    :message "Namespace lacks layer headings"
    :remediation "Add layer heading comments to organize code by abstraction level"}}

  {:rule/id :211-max-three-layers
   :rule/title "Maximum 3 layers per file"
   :rule/description "If you need more than 3 strata, split the namespace"
   :rule/severity :minor
   :rule/category "211"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["components/**/src/**/*.clj"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :content-scan
    :pattern "Layer\\s+[4-9]"}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "If you cross 3 layers, propose a split into another namespace.

    Max 3 strata per file keeps code comprehensible:
    - Layer 0: Pure helpers, no side effects
    - Layer 1: Orchestration depending on Layer 0
    - Layer 2: Entry points, side effects

    If Layer 3+ emerges, the namespace is doing too much. Split by:
    - Extracting pure helpers to a separate utilities namespace
    - Moving orchestration to a dedicated coordinator namespace
    - Separating concerns into distinct components"

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :warn
    :message "More than 3 layers detected"
    :remediation "Split into separate namespaces to maintain clarity"}}

  {:rule/id :211-comment-block-last
   :rule/title "Rich comment block must be last"
   :rule/description "Reserve the very bottom of file for (comment ...) section. No def/defn after it."
   :rule/severity :minor
   :rule/category "211"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["**/*.clj" "**/*.cljc"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :content-scan
    :pattern "\\(comment[\\s\\S]*?\\)\\s*\\n\\s*\\(def"}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "Ensure the last top-level form is a single (comment ...) block with quick REPL samples.

    The rich comment block serves as:
    - REPL-driven development playground
    - Usage examples for the namespace
    - Quick test cases during development

    Correct structure:
    (defn my-fn [x] ...)

    (comment
      ;; REPL examples
      (my-fn 42)
      (-> data transform process)
      )  ;; End of file

    No def/defn/defmacro should appear after the comment block."

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :warn
    :message "Code appears after (comment ...) block"
    :remediation "Move all def/defn above the comment block"}}]}
